The smell of old smoke and beer, along with the warm glow coming from the
fire makes this almost as cheerful and relaxing as being home. The room
has a peaceful atmosphere and you are guaranteed a degree of privacy in
here.',0,0,0);
This room tends to be used by adventurers planning to get rich and/or
famous in the magical plains to the south. The north wall has many tokens
attached to it by adventurers just before they leave. Some have their names
on them, others a simple message. The thing that strikes you is that there
are so many here. Many hundreds of expeditions have been planned and as you
think back you realise just how few ever succeed.',0,0,0);
The trees are filled with hawks, taking off, landing, but always very
aware of you. It is quite disconcerting how they watch you walk along.
though you are very glad they seem content to sit and watch. There are
enough of these powerful birds to overwhelm even mighty fighters.',0,0,0);
This appears a busy and thriving community, they appear to favour the round
hut style of building, though there are some larger, different structures
among them. Perhaps the most surprising thing of all is its size. This is
actually a large community, much more so than you have been led to believe.',0,0,0);
There look to be three main paths around the village, the west cuts through
the middle of the community. The northern one goes past a large, surely
important building, while the southern path leads past some wooden frames
down to what could be a coral. There are a few trees here as well providing
shade and again you can see watching hawks sitting amongst the branches.',0,0,0);
There are small offerings placed at the base of the pole, mostly of grain or
small hand crafted items. The hut to the north is made of solid wooden logs
and there are elements of it that have been carved by the same hand that
has made this pole. Considering its size the crafter of the poles must be
held in some high esteem.',0,0,0);
At the far end you can make out a pallet where someone can sleep and near
the pallet a small shrine where incense is burning. A blank pole has been
placed here but not yet started, the pole has been placed on a series of
blocks and wedged in securely. You wonder why the pole is not being carved,
it looks to have been resting here for some time now.',0,0,0);
It may well be that some celebration will be staged soon. Certainly there
are plenty of smiles and cheerful remarks. It could be fortunate to have
arrived now. If the tribe are in a good mood you might be able to get an
advantage out of it.',0,0,0);
The tapestries are richly woven, bright colours and patterns, mostly
geometric shapes, but occasionally there is one with an image woven into
it. The trophies tend to capture most of your attention, the heads of
vanquished beasts, but definitely not your average beasts. Among them are
the heads of a manticore, a hippogriff and what must be a basilisk though
its eyes have been removed.',0,0,0);
This is the northern end of the hall, near the exit and generally where the
lesser members of the tribe will sit when celebrating. There is a higher
chance of being disturbed and suffering drafts and other minor irritants.
The table is old and made from planks of worn oak. The surface scarred from
many knives, not all used for meals.',0,0,0);
On some frames are stretched out animal skins being cured and prepared for
the many uses that the tribe will put such material to. There are a wide
number of different skins, from horse to bear to fox to a silky looking
pelt which seems similar to, but different from a lions.',0,0,0);
The hut opposite the coral looks to be some sort of storage area, a simple
cloth flap is visible instead of a door and inside there looks to be some
items, though you cannot quite see what from out here. It being opposite the
coral you would expect the stuff in there to be horse related.',0,0,0);
You look around and see leather halters, brushes, blankets and many other
horsey things but no bits or whips. No saddles either, except one and this
one makes up for the fact there are no others. Made of the finest leather,
chiselled with beautiful artistic designs, it is a marvel to behold. Silver
worked links and rings add to the effect as does the ivory saddle horn. Its
value is incredible and as you approach you realise it is worth even more
than you thought as it glows with a soft blue light, magical! You go to lift
it but find your hands cannot go near it, something is making it so you
cannot touch it. You assume that part of the magic must be a protection
against thieves.',0,0,0);
As you look around a barbarian brings another horse, and this one is not
tamed, not in the least. A large black stallion, he looks angry and
dangerous, though very handsome. You watch the barbarian try and break him
and be thrown four times. Each time the horse lunges at him but he easily
evades and leaps back onto it. The fifth time his companion stops him and
mounts the horse. This time the horse does not have it his own way and the
red haired barbarian is still sitting when the horse can barely stand
lathered in sweat. Once he knows the horse is his, he dismounts and walks
away out of the coral.',0,0,0);
The homes here are mostly of the round hut style favoured in this tribe.
Coming in a wide range of sizes they all follow the same building principle.
The brick and wood circular walls with rush roofs is a simple style to
follow but effective. There is an empty area as you move eastwards which
cleanly separates the homes from the coral you can see there.',0,0,0);
There are a lot of huts, quite closely clustered together here. The path
runs generally to the south of them and a lot face out to the open fields.
Considering that there are so many huts around here there is little mess or
debris collecting. It would appear that the barbarians do not waste much,
or at least not enough to litter their camp.',0,0,0);
The owner of this hut looks to spend as little time here as possible. Though
it does feel abandoned it does not have a lived in feel either. This is
more a stopover than anything else. The discarded items pushed into the
corners suggest as much.',0,0,0);
The brick-work of the well is fairly new, less than ten years old. This
is because in a raid by a wilier tribe of bugbears the old well was
targeted and destroyed. The bugbears had hoped to drive away the
barbarians by depriving them of water. Obviously this didn''t happen
though it did inconvenience them terribly. As a result the well is in a
building similar to other dwelling of the tribe in an attempt to make
it harder to be targeted.',0,0,0);
This is almost a built up area by the tribes standards. It may be down to
the excellent views to the south or maybe the harder, rockier ground gives
a better building base. Whatever the reason it is in this area that most
homes have been built. There is also a large hut here, unlike many others
it has no windows and the bottom three feet of the walls are made of well
fitted stone.',0,0,0);
The hut has been carefully designed to keep the deprivations of rodents and
other pests to a minimum. The lower walls are all of carefully placed stone
and the walls up to around five feet have downwards facing nails placed in
them. The barrels are placed on stools with similar arrangements to the
walls except for one which has a single leg clear of impediments. On top of
that barrel is a clay jar full of an undetectable rat poison. The meats hang
from the ceiling hopefully out of the reach of things like rats though this
is difficult to achieve.',0,0,0);
Opposite the field is a large hut, and one who''s owner is held in some
esteem. This is not the traditional style of hut found here, but almost a
cabin. The walls have been made by driving the timber poles into the ground
and then plastering over it all with clay. The roof is still of rushes, but
the quality of work here is much higher, almost as good as a full thatch.',0,0,0);
This is obviously where the hawks are trained, though you would have thought
they needed little to hunt. A barbarian lad is running across the field with
a long rope trailing behind. At the end of the rope is a cloth bag bouncing
around in an awkward fashion. You watch as one of the hawks suddenly stoops
and tries for the bag, narrowly missing. The hawkers seem to think the close
miss was still a find attempt.',0,0,0);
There are a couple of small ponds here in which you can hear the croaking of
frogs and other small creatures. The grass is quite tall and there are a
lot of nettles here. You are not quite sure what the purpose of all this is
but you feel it does indeed serve a purpose, though one hidden from you.',0,0,0);
Off to one side of the hut there is even a small vegetable patch with some
nicely growing tomatoes. It exudes an air of tranquility and peace. Whomever
lives here seems to be someone with few cares. Moving around you can see the
vegetable garden extends behind the hut as well and it more extensive than
you first realised.',0,0,0);
To the east you can make out a cleared space and it looks like the hut has
something to do with it. A bone archway frames the path to the northeast
and you can make out that the bone theme seems to continue further up that
path, interesting. Looking further west, past the hut you can see that the
land is quite broken and rough, with many boulders and small trees. A salty
tang is in the air suggesting that the sea must be quite close by.',0,0,0);
owner of the hut seems not to be inclined towards material wealth though
they have an appreciation for the more artistic things. The rugs covering
the floor are of excellent quality and the walls have been plastered and
then painted. First a white background then with a running scene depicting
some battle or other. Possibly the most interesting thing about the work is
the tower in the background. It looks somehow familiar to you.',0,0,0);
Before any may enter the Circle of Honour they must remove all anger, hatred
or any other negative emotions from their hearts. The purity of the circle
is the purity of combat and the chief and shaman preside over any battles
fought there. So strong is the custom, and so ingrained into the psyche of
the tribe is this ritual that simply entering this hut is enough for most
to shed their darker impulses. The shaman has also added heavy enchantments',0,0,0);
No matter how noble the tribe or exalted its members, there are times when
nothing but a trial of strength is needed to resolve a dispute. It must be
something in all the fresh air they get. The circle is, as usual, a large
plain chalked area. The earth is hard packed and quite even.',0,0,0);
The fence is made of bones, lots of them. The southwest end is fairly low,
but as you move more and more to the northeast the height of the fence
increases until it is almost eight feet high. Walking in this direction
gives you the curious feeling that you are sinking lower and lower with each
step. As far as you can tell there are no human, elven or dwarfish bones
used, but you can definitely make out orcish and bugbears as contributors.',0,0,0);
The hawks the tribe are bonded with nest on the face of the Divide and thus
the people here have become renowned climbers simply through necessity.
There are also tales of a place, sacred to the barbarians where they can
test their mettle. Few take the tests until fully ready as the loss of kudos
amongst their peers would be massive. Senior members of the tribe are
believed to specify the tests that the warriors must accomplish.',0,0,0);
The path north is little used though still clear. From what you can see
it generally follows a northern route leading directly to the cliff face
of the great divide. The hawk tribe have created a Hall of Heroes there,
but none will say by whom, or how it was done, there are rumours that
magic is involved but the tribe remains tightlipped and the rumours
remain unconfirmed.',0,0,0);
The fork is clear and the path leading northwest looks even wilder and less
used than the main road. In some places it has almost faded completely, so
few use it. Looking up the northwest fork you think you can make out a
marker of some sort. If there is one it will be warning of some sort of
danger, but you are not sure as it is almost entirely obscured by a large
bush from here.',0,0,0);
You feel that there is more to it than excessive shading, certainly other
areas that you travelled along have the same conditions and much more
luxurious growths. You wonder if there is a curse or presence in the area,
you cannot feel anything, no sudden coldness or your hackles rising. You
don''t even feel a hostile gaze on your back. In fact there is nothing, you
wonder if the soil here is just very poor.',0,0,0);
The south looks worse than this so there must be something in the soil which
causes poor growth. The land here is on a slight rise and you notice that
there is a rough circular area, maybe four hundred feet diameter affected.
The land to the south is its rough centre. It is also clear that the worst
part is at the lowest point in the dip, this would indicate something large
falling to earth there, though you saw nothing.',0,0,0);
The perches are poles with bars across the top, looking like the letter ''T''
and between the two largest and sturdiest of them is slung a hammock. It is
not really noticeable from outside, but there is a permanently open flap in
the rush roof through which the birds may leave if they chose to. From the
lack of possessions it is clear the owner of this place is concerned only
with his charges and nothing else.',0,0,0);
Trees wrapped in shadows are on both sides of the path, but while you
keep to it you are safe. There is almost a boundary between path and
wood that should be visible. The shadows seem to start out of nothing
and gather strength and darkness very quickly.',0,0,0);
One of the dogs, well wolves are not quite that small, emerges from the
kennel with a hostile glance in your direction. These are hunting dogs and
are full of confidence in their ability to take down even the largest of
foes. You would not want to have to run from a pack of these beasts, you
don''t rate your chances too highly.',0,0,0);
You notice a small totem pole, barely four feet high is in the middle of the
bushes. Curiously the three faces carved in it are not stylised as you have
seen elsewhere but look to be accurate representations of real people. You
wonder who they were and what they did to be honoured in this way.',0,0,0);
The home does not appear locked or barred, but it is clear that there is
no one there. The smithy in contrast is a hive of activity. Warriors seem
to be continually breaking weapons and need them repaired and one warrior
enters with a heavy chest and then comes out with a gleaming sword of a
metal you cannot identify.',0,0,0);
While looking around one of the tribesmen comes in and explains that this
was the home of one a warrior, ancient with the burden of time. He decided
that rather than die in bed he would indeed die in battle. Though many
tried to dissuade him, for he was well liked. In the recent battle with a
tribe of bugbears he stood at the front and accounted for fully eight of
the foul beasts before he was brought down. The warrior says even now the
tribe are reluctant to let anyone else into his home feeling that somehow
his presence remains.',0,0,0);
From its size you can clearly see that it is of dwarven manufacture. A truly
beautiful construction. The bellows, even though artfully wrought still need
two large handlers to get the full draught needed. The smith is working on a
weapon and it is a wonderful one too! Already you can see that it will be a
longsword, but it is made of a silver and steel alloy. This alloy is not one
you have come across before but you believe it would make wonderful
weapons.',0,0,0);
It appears this is an overspill area for the barbecue. Some prefer to be in
a less crowded area and this is where they tend to come. There are plenty
logs grouped nicely as seats for friends to sit on while chatting.',0,0,0);
Beside the fire pits is a large even square of land. It is packed hard and
grass-less as if many feet have trodden it. In fact it looks like a dance
square similar to those found in the farming communities near Highmarket.
Along two of the sides are long, weathered benches and along the last side
is a single massive stone slab. How it got here you have no idea but it
looks as if the musicians probably sit on it to play. It seems that the
tribe like many others needs little excuse to party and this would be the
most obvious spot to have it if the weather is good enough.',0,0,0);
Most homes are stone and timber but this one has managed to convert
entirely to stone. Sadly it is dwarfed by the nearby lodge to the west
which by tribal standards is a truly magnificent building.',0,0,0);
Typically the barbarian tribes do not go in for blocky furniture preferring
to use free form methods like cushions and low stools. They do like chests
and other fancy storage items for some reason. It may well be one of those
oneupmanship things, ''not only do I have expensive weapons but I need
somewhere expensive to keep them''. It seems the tribes are no different
from anyone else in the end.',0,0,0);
The building is almost as large as the fest-hall but not quite as normal. The
lip of the roof, as far as you can tell, all the way around is decorated
with teeth. They are all fangs, no molars or human style molars. The
previous owners of these teeth liked their food fresh. To cap it all the
teeth have all been silver plated. It reminds you of a decorated home during
a yuletide festival. The walls have been painted a pale blue and running
around the lower edge of the wall are eye-watering runes.',0,0,0);
There seems to be a lot of needle and threads here and also a lot of rubber
plants. One of the shaman''s apprentices is dealing with a warrior with a
lot of gouges along his arm, puncture marks too. Some of that thread you
noticed is being used to stitch him up and here you find out why so many
rubber plants. A paste is applied to the deep punctures and then a plant is
cut. The sap is dripped over the top of the paste in effect sealing it in.',0,0,0);
For a moment you forget to breath then you realise that this is one beast
that is not going to attack. Its been stuffed and mounted! It still
possesses an air of menace though, its nature before it died quite clear.
Looking around you see all sorts of junk here, the shaman is as bad a
hoarder as any mage you have met. One thing that does stand out is a small
mithril forge with several blocks of silver beside it. A medallion,
obviously freshly crafted, lies beside it while it cools down. The forge
also has a pale blue glow about it as well.',0,0,0);
This hut looks to be some sort of storage area for the tribe. It is made of
stone and has the only lockable door. The door glows with a faint orange
hue, not something you have seen before in door magics. It does make the
hut look very interesting though as while the door appears normal wood, the
lock is a flat cyan plate with an etched feather shape in it.',0,0,0);
This makes for a winding journey often out of view of any serious landmarks,
excepting of course the Great Divide. There are also plenty of trees but
here you notice, very few hawks. Looking around you realise this is the
first time that there have been no hawks visible at all. After all this
time its become quite unsettling.',0,0,0);
The blue totems are something you have heard of. They always lead towards
something that is dangerous. Rather than be a means of warning away members
of the tribe, these are an open invitation to face what ever lies at the end
of the journey. The poles are always blue but the feathers can vary, white
signifying minimal danger, yellow signifying that it is quite dangerous
while blue says it is very dangerous.',0,0,0);
The breeze feels somehow strange you back up the path a distance and it
stops, as you move forwards it starts blowing again. You do this manoeuvre
several times and come to the conclusion the breeze is constant, it just
fades away at a certain point. You have not come across this effect before
and it is not one you like. You feel yourself moving into a combat ready
stance.',0,0,0);
The breeze is constant now and quite strong. It seems to be coming from
a point below the edge of the cliff. You can see that it is roughly
where the path ends at the lip of the cliff. With care you walk up to
the edge and look down at a series of steps leading down to a ledge
below. Looking more carefully you can see a series of handholds carved
into the face of the cliff.',0,0,0);
As you move from hold to hold you notice something disturbing. It looks like
someone has used this route while bleeding heavily. Bloodied finger prints
are in each recess and there are plenty of smears on the cliff face. This
has had to be recent as there was a heavy rain several days ago.
Your mind drifts back to the danger markers above, looks like the shaman
was not understating the problem.',0,0,0);
The mess is likely several days old but you know that the cause just has
to be around still. The route to finding it is not at all appealing. A
hole, barely three feet high and four across leads into the cliff.',0,0,0);
Any half-giant using this passage is not at all happy, Only by wriggling
and squirming can they get along this passage. Should anything attack
them here they would be at best dogmeat. The smaller races may be able to
get through a lot quicker but even they are handicapped enough to not
want to stay here.',0,0,0);
It is still not very large but there is easily enough to accommodate any
individual. Further down the tunnel there is a blue-green glow, flickering
and ethereal. You are not sure what is causing it but looking down you see
the bloodstains earlier noted on the cliff face. What is more disconcerting
is the other completely dried stains, there are a lot of them.',0,0,0);
The tunnel ends at a large hole, easy enough for two men to walk through
side by side. The hole is interesting and a little bit weird, the edges of
the rock seem to fade away into nothingness rather then end normally. The
hole has not been cut out of the rock, more that the rock has been
encouraged ''to go away'' At the very edges of the hole your fingers pass
through the rock though they tingle when you do it.',0,0,0);
You are quick to realise that the air elemental has brought its home into the
material plane. How it can do this you have no idea and you wonder if it may
have been accidental. You immediately notice a frosty wind blowing through,
chilling everything it touches. There are several cages large enough to hold
hawks, they are empty now, but one has a feather in it still. The elemental
is doing something with them, but you cannot tell what from this scant
evidence.',0,0,0);
Two lean-to''s are here, one each side of the central cave. The entrance to
the cave has been decorated with carvings, ugly ones. Looking at them a
little closely it is obvious they are trying to explain the raptures of the
change which as you read it are no raptures at all, quite the opposite. You
turn your attention to the cave itself, you have seen few things so
foreboding, but the darkness in there is high on your list.',0,0,0);
You can see where a panel in the shack can be moved to allow moonlight
onto the shrine, for ceremonies but the actual shrine itself is somewhat
disturbing. It focuses on the duality element associated with the moon,
perhaps not surprising considering the locals. The shrine is a large
sheet of crystal with a small mask mounted in the middle. Looking at the
mask one way shows a pretty girls face, another angle shows that of a
bloodthirsty beast.',0,0,0);
The three tunnels look roughly equal, none seem to offer you any incentives
to follow them at all. At the moment you have no real idea which might be
safer or more dangerous. You do feel that staying in one place for any
length of time could be very bad for your health, terminal even.',0,0,0);
You guess that this tunnel has been manufactured, quite possibly in the last
few years. There are a lot of tool marks on the tunnel walls and you assume
it is this awkward to navigate as a design feature. It would certainly slow
down an attackers to the den.',0,0,0);
Only hobbits and maybe some smaller dwarfs or gnomes would not have to
stoop here. Again you can see plenty of chiselling and you realise that
the tunnel height is perfectly adequate for wolves as well as hobbits.
